{{Shrine |name= Shioya Shrine |religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image= [[File:Shioya-jinja 03.jpg|270px]] |location= {{ill|Ōminato, Ise|ja|大湊 (伊勢市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōminato, Ise|qq=}}, [[:en:Ise, Mie|Ise, Mie]], [[:en:Mie Prefecture|Mie Prefecture]] |latitude_deg= 34 | latitude_min = 31 | latitude_sec = 34.4 |longitude_deg= 136 |longitude_min = 43 | longitude_sec = 47.1 |map= Japan Mie |deity= {{ill|Shiotsuchi-no-Oji|lt=Shiotsuchi-no-Oji|lt=Shiotsuchi no Oji|ja|シオツチノオジ|lt=Shiotsuchi-no-Oji|lt=Shiotsuchi no Oji|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiotsuchi no Oji|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to シオツチオジ}} (鹽土老翁) |Rank= {{ill|Toyouke Daijingu|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Daijingu|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Daijingu|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} Subordinate Shrine |founded= Before [[Enryaku]] 23 (804) |main_hall= [[:en:Shinmei-zukuri|Shinmei-zukuri]] |other_names= *Myōjin-san* (明神さん), *Minato no Myōjin-sama* (湊の明神さま), *Shioya Myōjin* (塩屋明神) |pilgrimage_sites= |annual_festival= |rituals= [[:en:Kannamesai Festival|Kannamesai]] }}
[[File:Shioya-jinja 04.jpg|thumb|Panoramic view of the shrine grove with a torii gate visible at the entrance.]]
'''Shioya Shrine''' (志宝屋神社, *Shioya Jinja*) is a [[:en:Setsumatsusha|subordinate shrine (sessha/massha)]] of {{ill|Toyouke Daijingu|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Daijingu|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Daijingu|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} (the Outer Shrine of [[:en:Ise Shrine|Ise Grand Shrine]]). It Ranks 8th among the eight subordinate shrines of the Outer Shrine<ref>Ujiyamada City Office, ed. (1929): pp.13, 15</ref>.
The enshrined {{ill|Kami|lt=Kami|lt=Deity|ja|Kami|lt=Kami|lt=Deity|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/deity|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to カミ}} is the god of salt production. In its location at {{ill|Ōminato, Ise|ja|大湊 (伊勢市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōminato, Ise|qq=}}, [[:en:Ise, Mie|Ise, Mie]], [[:en:Mie Prefecture|Mie Prefecture]], salt production was once a flourishing industry<ref name="gk">Gakken Publishing (2013): p.63</ref>.
== Overview == {{ill|Shiho-ya Shrine|ja|志宝屋神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiho-ya Shrine|qq=}} is located in Ōminato Town, Ise City, which was known as a shipbuilding town until the 20th century<ref name="ic">Ise Bunka-sha (2008): p.46</ref>. Ōminato Town is situated on a river delta surrounded by levees<ref name="ic"/>. Approaching from the Misato Town area of Ise City along the levee road of the [[:en:Miyagawa|Miyagawa (Mie)]] River, one can see the forest of Shiho-ya Shrine<ref name="ic"/>. This sacred forest is referred to as the "Forest of Cormorants" (鵜の森)<ref name="gk"/>. The shrine grounds cover an area of approximately 2,257.85 m²<ref name="uy">Ujiyamada City Hall (1929): p.15</ref>.
Locally, the shrine is affectionately called "Myōjin-san" (明神さん)<ref name="km">{{Cite web|ja|url=http://www.kankomie.or.jp/kataribe/course_11725.html|title=A Historical Walk in the Shipbuilding Town of Ōminato Part 1|work=Visit Mie|publisher=Mie Prefecture Tourism Federation|accessdate=2013-09-29|archiveurl=https://megalodon.jp/2013-0929-0920-23/www.kankomie.or.jp/kataribe/course_11725.html|archivedate=2013-09-29}}</ref>, "Minato no Myōjin-sama" (湊の明神さま), and "Shioya Myōjin" (塩屋明神)<ref name="gk"/><ref name="ic"/>.
== Enshrined deity == The enshrined deity is '''Shiotsuchi-no-Oji''' (鹽土老翁)<ref name="ic"/>. He is revered as the god of salt production as well as the guardian deity of maritime routes<ref name="gk"/><ref name="ic"/>. Additionally, he is widely worshiped by local residents as a deity of safe childbirth<ref name="ic"/>.
There is a tradition that a sacred spirit (mitama) was transferred (bunrei) from [[:en:Shiogama shrine|Shiogama Shrine]] in Shiogama City, Miyagi Prefecture<ref name="km"/>.
== History == Based on the definition of auxiliary shrines of the Ise Grand Shrine, Shiho-ya Shrine was established before the compilation of the ''Enryaku Gishiki-chō'', that is, before 804 (Enryaku 23)<ref>Ise Bunka-sha (2008): p.22</ref>. The area surrounding the shrine was known as "Ōshioya Village," where many villagers were engaged in salt production for offerings to the Ise Grand Shrine<ref name="km"/>. Regarding Shiho-ya Shrine, {{ill|Sakurai Katsunosuke|ja|櫻井勝之進|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakurai Katsunosuke|qq=}} remarked<ref>Sakurai (1970): p.93</ref>: {{Quotation|Although 'Shioya' is said to be the old name of what later flourished as the port town of Ōminato, if the shrine was still considered a subordinate shrine at the time, perhaps it was just a small village with smoke rising from salt kilns. |Sakurai Katsunosuke, ''Ise Jingū'', p.93}}
The shrine building was destroyed along with 1,000 homes in Ōshioya Village during the [[:en:1498 Meiō earthquake|Meiō earthquake]] on August 25, 1498 (Julian calendar: September 11, 1498)<ref name="km"/>. It was later rebuilt in 1644 (Kan'ei 21) and has survived to the present day<ref name="km"/>.
== Access == * By Bus: About a 7-minute walk (approximately 600 m) from the "Tokuda" bus stop or about a 9-minute walk (approximately 750 m) from the "Nishimachi" bus stop serviced by [[:en:Mie Kotsu|Mie Kotsu]] buses. * By Car: From the "Shinkai Kita" intersection on National Route 23 (Nansei Bypass), head north via {{ill|Mie Prefectural Route 748|ja|三重県道748号大湊宮町停車場線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mie Prefectural Route 748|qq=}}, approximately 8 minutes (about 2.9 km). There are no parking facilities nearby.
